With the best intentions, usually, to help someone focus where they might need some work. >>38058965
What the other comments said. Generalizing for "animals" doesn't work. You have to go species by species. The eye structure of an octopus could well be the single most advanced eye structure evolved on Earth. That we have discovered so far. We don't have to assume an octopus waifur to realize the implications; there could be (depending upon world building) any number of animals with advanced eye structure that makes them wonder how humans are able to "see" at all.

This post did make me instantly consider something that I rarely see addressed in any furry community literature. Our world building almost always revolves around a "DAILY" life schedule. There are exceptions, of course, but so many stories and heir plots incorporate the human world view of the fake "day-schedule" for nearly all activities.

An anthro world would be a 24-hour/day activity world. Different species have different needs & abilities during different parts of the day/night cycle. Some species might be even more locked into a day schedule than humans, being genetically almost incapable of functioning at night. Others, just the opposite ... most feline predators are fully awake and peak-functioning during twilight and into the night.

A world with a dozen or three species across these spectrums would never have developed a day-cycle prejudice from the beginning of history like we have. It would ALWAYS have had species going on-shift & off-shift every few hours throughout a 24-hour day-night schedule. The most common thing governing all species would be the lunar cycles, if we use Earth or an Earth-like planet for their world. All would not just have eyes specialized for their cycle, but brains & body chemistry.

Worlds with multiple moons, or worlds that are moons around larger planets, wouldn't even have a lunar cycle in common. It gets to be an extremely complex set of hypotheticals if life can even be Earth-similar for such systems without the strong, distinct lunar cycle we have.

Anonymous Wed 21 Apr 2021 05:08:58 No.38069628 Report

>>38069310
I assume you're not shipping out soon, so plan out your weeks and follow a workout plan. Boot camp will drastically change your body for better or for worse depending on each person due to the radically different diet and activity each day. You burn off way more calories during the crucible than you get from the little stuff you absorb from MREs. Skinny guys turn lean because they ate more and bulky guys lose a shit ton of weight because they don't eat as much as they used to.
If your local park has a pull up bar then it's all the equipment you really need. Focus on pull-ups and crunches because one more count of those gives the same amount of points as 30 seconds off your run time. Since you're still at 0 you want to work on reverse pull-ups and push-ups to get yourself started. Even in boot camp after lights I waited a bit before going to the quarterdeck's pull-up bar to improve more before the next PST(You have two in the training cycle).
When you're in training, avoid injury as much as possible if you don't want to stay behind. I was lucky and made it through with no setbacks, but there's people I know that stayed for 5-9 months due to injuries, and if you're unlucky the injured recruit platoons treat you even shittier compared to regular companies. The basic training system wants to get as much people graduated as possible and into the fleet, so they will not send your ass away unless you tell the docs you're depressed or suicidal.

This is a lot of off-topic shit so I apologize for the dump. Have a thicc Judy.
